The paper deals with distributed computing and network topology, which are central topics in the sub-categories of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC), Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS), Computational Complexity (cs.CC), Computational Geometry (cs.CG), and Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI). The paper specifically focuses on the CONGEST model, which is a well-known model in distributed computing, and investigates the amount of local information that is sufficient for a central entity to compute certain properties of the network topology. This suggests that the paper is likely to be relevant to these sub-categories.
